"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105141","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-02","<p>My Noble friend the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Work and Pensions (Lords) replied to the hon. Member on 27 March 2019.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-04-02T14:15:21.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105141/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105141/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-26","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when she plans to respond to the letter of 10 January 2019 from the hon. Member for Glasgow Central on behalf of her constituent Mr Neil Rothnie.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","237117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105142","Department for Education","false","2019-04-04","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. The Department does not collect information relating to the published admissions numbers of individual schools.</p><p>All school admission authorities must set a published admissions number (PAN). This is the number of pupils the school will admit at their normal point of entry, for example, to the reception year of a primary school.</p><p>Admission authorities are not required to consult before increasing their PAN. They must, however, notify the local authority of any intention to do so.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-04-04T15:46:12.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105142/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105142/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105142/answer/previousversion/111136","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-03-26","Schools: Birkenhead","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which schools in Birkenhead have expanded their intake without undertaking a public consultation in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","237009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105143","Home Office","false","2019-04-03","<p>Immigration is a reserved matter and the Government’s immigration policy applies to the whole of the United Kingdom. We consider the needs of the UK as a whole and are committed to developing an immigration system that serves the national interest.</p><p><br>We have set out our proposals for the future border and immigration system that would operate after 2021, in a White Paper published in December. As set out in the White Paper, we will provide for a single, global immigration system that will be based on skills rather than on where someone comes from – and is designed to attract international talent and work in the best interests of the UK economy as a whole.</p><p><br>Scotland’s particular circumstances and needs for skilled labour continue to be accounted for through the Scotland-specific Shortage Occupation List which allows immigration to address the gaps in Scotland’s labour market. The list broadly reflects the wider UK Shortage Occupation List, suggesting that Scotland’s skills needs are largely aligned with the rest of the UK.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-04-03T16:28:08.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105143/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105143/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-26","Migrant Workers: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the 18 per cent reduction in the number of National Insurance registrations in Scotland by overseas workers between 2015 and 2018, what steps his Department is taking to encourage overseas workers to Scotland.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","237118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105144","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-01","<p>The Department agrees that it is important that there is appropriate support for patients on discharge from hospital. All patients should have a discharge assessment to determine the level of care they will need upon discharge from hospital, including whether a care plan is needed.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan makes clear the importance of moving care into the community, and this Government is committed to achieving this. It commits an extra £4.5 billion a year by 2023/24 of investment in primary care and community health services.</p><p> </p><p>The National Health Service is currently developing the Implementation Framework for the Long Term Plan. Improving discharge from hospital and supporting patients to recover their independence in the most appropriate setting will be taken into account within this framework.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-04-01T11:45:27.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105144/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105144/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-26","Home Care Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has made an assessment of the implications for his policies of the recommendations in the Red Cross report entitled Home to the Unknown: Getting hospital discharge right; and whether he is taking steps to introduce an independence check prior to discharge or within 72 hours of going home, as recommended by the Red Cross.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","237050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105146","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-01","<p>We have completed clerically collecting Management Information on live Youth Obligation Support Programme participants as at the end of January 2019. This is in the process of being quality assured before we consider plans to publish this data.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","236985 ; 236986","2019-04-01T12:13:29.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105146/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105146/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-26","Employment Schemes: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2019 to Question 216920, what plans she has to publish Youth Obligation outcome data; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","236984"
